column14:
These boots are super cute and are reasonably priced. They are more of a fashion cowboy boot, so if you're looking for a pair of boots you can go stomping around on the farm or rodeo with, these may not be the boots for you. It's not the sturdiest boot made,( when you tap on the heel you can hear it is hollow), but that is to be expected from a moderately priced boot. I bought these for my daughter who is a true size 8, and I got an 8 1/2 since I know she'll wear socks with them. Without socks, they were just a tad bit big, with regular socks, they fit nicely.

On another note, when I first removed the boots from the box, it had a very strong smell. I got the tan colored boots and I'm not sure if the strong smell came from the chemicals or dye they used to color it tan like leather, but the smell reminded me of some kind of varnish or stain. The odor was so strong I had to set the boots outside for the whole day to air out, and the smell eventually went away. BUT, I would still purchase this boot again.

column13: These shoes were perfect. They came in my size
column14: These shoes were perfect. They came in my size, fit perfectly both in length and width, and were comfortable for all day wear.  So you may be asking, why the 1-star rating?  After 3-4 months of wear, not even daily, the top of the sole began coming loose.  I figured it happens, but thought that a company like Sperry would stand behind their shoes and offer a repair or exchange since I always believed they cared about their customers and high-quality shoes.  I quickly realized they offer no such thing, and will only replace / exchange unworn shoes within 45 days.  I am not typically hard on my shoes - I have several pair of other brands, who shall go nameless in this review, which I've worn for close to a decade and while they appear worn still fit and are not falling apart.  I LOVED these shoes while I owned them, but I can't bring myself to buy another pair at these prices for risk they will fall apart again.

column6: C Label Women's Figaro-4
column14:
This shoe is cute, I had no comfort issues above the foot bed. The straps, buckle, etc. are very soft and flexible (not leather but leather-like). My issue is the foot bed. It is difficult to walk in these shoes without a platform or softer foot bed. I wear 4+ inch heels on a regular basis so the height of the heel wasn't unfamiliar to me. The heel causes your weight to be pushed onto the ball of your feet as heels do, but there's no cushioning in that area which makes it difficult to walk for more than an hour or so. Shoe inserts help.

Regarding sizing, I wear 9.5 - 10. I ordered this shoe in 10. My feet fit w/a little overlap which isn't normal when I wear size 10.

column6: Genuine Leather Wallet Womens Clutch Zipper RFID Blocking
column14:
RFID chips are, frankly, quite scary. The other day a young woman stood behind me - unusually close - in a checkout line while I was paying. Normally, the next person in line would remain "about even" with the cashier as I used the credit/debit card terminal where groceries are bagged. However, as I was swiping my card, the young woman was less than a foot away and I was not certain if she were attempting to capture my card or was just plain oblivious to any sense of "personal space." She definitely was well within my comfort zone and, as a "senior citizen" it was clear there was no reason for her to be so close. I was concerned with the safety of my card. It got me thinking, so I did a search for the best products to prevent RFID capture.

I bought the Access Denied wallet for my wife and she loves it. The color of the wallet is a bit inaccurate on the web page and is even richer "in person." The quality is outstanding and she is very happy with every aspect of her wallet. In addition to the wallet providing excellent shielding, she has individual RFID blocking sleeves for each card. We highly recommend the Access Denied wallet!

One caution...while RFID chipped cards are secured in the wallet and sleeves, we have good confidence they are safe from capture by someone with bad intentions. However, when the card is actually out, uncovered and being used is a vulnerable time. The next time I am in line and someone like the young lady above gets too close, you can bet she/he will be asked to stand back before we uncover our card.

column6: ASICS Women's GEL-Galaxy 5 Running Shoe
column14:
I was very disappointed with these shoes. Asics has always been my go to running brand and I thought, even though these shoes were on the cheaper side, that Asics, as a brand, would not fail me. I was very wrong. I run about 30-40 miles a week and I needed a new pair after about 2 months, which is about the minimum distance a running shoe should last. I suppose, for a rather cheap shoe I should expect minimum performance but I expected more from Asics. Additionally, the wear was ridiculous on the shoe, on the left side of my left food the heal part was almost entirely worn down about a month and 2 weeks into use.

The worst part of the shoe though were the constant blisters on my pinky toes. The shoes were not tight, but the stitching, which connects the outer lining to the breathable fabric basically dug cut into my toes as I ran pealing the skin back.

column6: Altra Men's Paradigm 1.5 Running Shoe
column13: Finally, shoes that are shaped like your feet!
column14: I ran in Vibram Five Fingers for many years. The minimalist Five Fingers greatly improved my running form. I was free of knee and foot pain caused by traditional running shoes. I loved the Five Fingers, but was always having to lookout for loose rocks on the road or other things that are unpleasant to step on with a minimalist shoe. I decided to try the Altra Paradigm to see if I could find maximum cushioning and protection, but still have a shoe that allowed my toes to spread naturally. The Altra's did the trick. They still discourage heel striking while giving freedom for my toes to spread out into a comfortable position. The springy cushioning reminded me of those summer days as a kid bouncing on a trampoline, but after a week of running, my feet and knees are thankful for the soft landings and my eyes are free from constantly scanning the ground ahead of me for minor debris. Shoes that are shaped like feet are long overdue. Finally, I did not mark that the shoes provide good arch support. This requires explanation. The shoes provide less arch support than some traditional running shoes. I believe this is by design to give you the feel of running barefoot. column6: Unisex Retro Polarized Square Metal Wire Sunglasses - Sylvia & Sam With Spring Hinges
column14:
These sunglasses are made well. They have polarized lenses which add so much clarity to things, especially around water. They have springy arms which means that they won't stretch or break on larger faces and will spring back to fit smaller ones. I have the smoke color and the protections is good. They aren't too dark but they block the sun well while allowing me to clearly see everything. I originally got these for my husband and they really are a tad wide on me but I liked the clarity so I kept them. He loses. Ha!

The style is no nonsense. It isn't a celebrity style or anything but they look good with any outfit. They're simple but they don't distort or cause me to feel like I am walking crooked. I have some sunglasses that actually feel like they are prescription glasses - and not MY prescription. I don't know why that is but they make me feel a bit wobbly and there is a bit of distortion that bugs me. These glasses are crystal clear as far as distortion which is the main reason I kept them. That and the polarized lenses which many fashion sunglasses do not have.

They are, though, a bit wide as I mentioned. I think they are better for larger faces. But they don't slip down or cause any issues and they look fine on me. They're a big change from my usual oversize glasses or my mirrored wayfarers. I like them and feel they are high quality. They are pricier than many cheap fashion glasses but they're worth it because they are well made and have such good clarity. I am going with 4 stars. I wish they were a bit narrower but that's just because of my small face, not the glasses. These are a great choice for people who want sunglasses for hiking, fishing, and almost any activity. Really cheap sunglasses are fine for lounging by the pool but when you need clarity, you need to look beyond style to functionality.

I received these glasses at a reduced rate in exchange for my honest review. I am not affiliated with the company or seller and was not obligated to leave a positive review.positive review.

column6: Hippie Elephant Sling Crossbody Bag Shoulder Bag Purse Thai Top Zip Handmade New Color Black
column14: The first bag I received had a hole in one of the seams - not something I had noticed as a common issue from any of the other reviews. I sent it back immediately and ordered a replacement, which was handled seamlessly (no pun intended).  By the end of the week, I had a new bag, flawless, which I LOVE.  (Today I joked that I wished I had spent more time out of the house, so I could have a reason to be wearing my new purse.)  The item has a great, casual look, with an attractive print, and I love that it has the two zippers (for the main compartment and a small inside compartment), as well as being spacious.  While I wouldn't fill it up routinely with heavy items as the material isn't super thick (maybe a little thicker than a relatively well made t-shirt?), the bag appears to be well made, and it would be just right for carrying a bottle of water or book in addition to a wallet and other "typical" purse items.  The bag appears to be well made, and I anticipate it will serve me well for quite some time! Based on other reviews I had been concerned about the bag hanging too low on me at 5'2", but it sits with the opening near my waist and the bag itself at thigh-height, which I think adds to the casual look and I find ideal--it gives comfortable access to the bag while it's hung across my body, and the low positioning prevents any discomfort from the items in the bag being under one's arm while walking as with the positioning of a traditional purse. As someone who was dreading the hunt for a new purse after the strap on my old one finally broke (I'm not into purses, but can respect the practicality of having a way to carry items of necessity!), I've found one that I love so much, I'm almost happy my old one kicked the bucket. :)

column6: Orthofeet Asheville Comfort Arch Support Diabetic Mens Orthopedic Slippers
column14:
I am 6'2" and 400lb and let me tell you, those slippers are out of bounds amazing... They provide tons of support, tons of comfort and you'll feel you're walking on a cloud even if a really heavy guy like me. I used to never wear slippers because they were always bugging me, I prefered to walk barefoot, but when standing for a long time on the ceramic kitchen floor, my feet were hurting very bad, and sometimes for days... So I decided to try to find the best slippers for big guys. I found those were comming over and over again. Quality of craftmanship is perfect, in fact they will scream quality as soon as you'll open the box, they will last for years to come. Oh, and the lining is über soft.

Although I usually wear 4E wide shoes, I found the Medium (only width they had when I ordered) were perfect, those are made large, not narrow at all and you can adjust from both sides if you have a thick foot.

So, ladies, if you want to make your big man happy, buy him these...

column6: New Balance Men's M980V1 Fresh Foam Running Shoe
column13: These shoes are comfortable for me despite my low arches and unlike other ...
column14:
I don't usually write reviews, but I had to share my opinion of these Fresh Foam 980's. I am an Officer in the US Army and these shoes helped me considerably through Officer Candidate School (OCS). I wore them 6 days of week for workouts including runs, obstacle courses, cross-fit workouts, combatives training, and weight training. They survived regular abuse for this intensive 12 week course, plus 2 months of running 4 days a week, plus the wounded warrior half marathon. They finally bit the dust yesterday on a 9 mile hike of skyline drive in the Shenandoah valley. These shoes are comfortable for me despite my low arches and unlike other zero drop shoes they have considerable support with a lightweight design. I would recommend these shoes to anyone, I just bought my second pair and I will probably wear these shoes for running for the rest of my career. Thanks NewBalance!
2LT

column6: Altra Running Womens Superior 2 Trail Running Shoe
column13: Zero-drop, wide-toe-box shoes seem to be doing what over $600 in orthopedic inserts could not
column14:
I'm learning that my "arch support" orthopedics were actually causing more problems than they were solving. Plantar's Fasciitis got better but the toes (bunions and other problems) got worse. The naturally-shaped toe box, toe spacers, and Zero-drop shoes are working much better for me, and I am transitioning into them as directed, for the most part.

They may save me from bunion surgery, which is far more gruesome than I ever thought it would be (cut the bone and bolt it back into place?). I thought that dropping the orthopedic "molded" inserts ($680 ones, I might add) that the Plantar's Fasciitis might come back, but so far it's better than it was when I had the orthopedic "arch-support" inserts.

I strongly recommend the reading (and products) at "Naturalfootgear.com". It takes time, but even if I still need surgery, I can avoid having the problems come back again.

This is the perfect shoe for the first stage of transitioning into wide-toe (naturalistic foot ware), zero-drop shoes. I'm delighted with the results so far, about two weeks in.

column13: AWESOME WOODS N\ STREAM  1400  SNAKE BITE BOOTS"
column14: I am deathly afraid of  SNAKES !!!!  of any kind ,especially the RATTLERS  we have here on the High desert of Central Oregon.  Some of my favorite places to fish and hunt, are in SNAKE  infested areas. I saw these New  Woods and Stream 1400 Snake Bite Boots, by Weinbrenner Shoe Company ,one of Americas oldest and finest quality  shoe companies  and they were just what I was looking for. They are 19" tall from sole to boot top. The coolest thing is they come in a Mossy Oak Brand Camo pattern. They are X-Streamly waterproof. They are also made of the finest leather and heavy duty thick, cordura style,  snake proof materials. The zipper is thick and beefy ,for a long life in the field. The soles and toe guards, provide multi surface traction, lateral stability and are self cleaning. These boots are also very lightweight. They have handles on the top of the boots ,for easy slip in comfort. I have tested these boots in many different, in the field conditions ,muddy,slippery very wet, immersed in water,rocky terrain, except an actual Snake Bite and find them to be of the very highest quality materials and workmanship. I give these snake bite boots my very highest recommendation for,overall comfortability and peace of mind, when I am rooting around in the desert , in snake territory. { FISHGRILLER APPROVED }

column13: The frames are a wrap around style with a comfortable rubberized nose piece
column14:

The frames are a wrap around style which provides full sun protection a with a comfortable rubberized nose piece. column14:
I had sent a pair of Asics Gel Foundation 8's back to AsicsAmerica because the soles were peeling after just 7 months of wear and because they were still under the 2 year defective product warranty, they sent me a free pair of these Gel Fortify.
They are SOOOOOO COMFORTABLE!
I am 6'3", 240lbs with flat feet and I have to wear my Asics all day at the physical therapy clinic where I work. I have had these for a few weeks, but I can already tell I will have no problems wearing these for 8 hrs a day at the clinic. I have been wearing Asics for 10 years now and this is like my 7th pair, but they are probably the MOST comfortable pair I've owned! It's important to note that when I buy my Asics, I don't buy their cheap models either because I wear a 15 (4E) which is like double wide plus I need the Dynamic Duomax for my severe over-pronation. As a matter of fact, I may buy another pair as a backup for when these wear out!
I DEFINITELY recommend this model. They seem true to width as well as size and I can't over emphasize the amount of cushion and support. As soon as I tried them on out of the box it was like walking on clouds. I would give them 6 stars out of 5!

column6: Maui Jim Makaha Polarized Sunglasses
column13: Comfortable lightweight frames, terrible quality lens and Maui Jim support
column14: We (I bought them for my spouse) have owned 2 pair of these MJ Makaha 405-10, the first pair lasted about 24 months before the lens cracked at the screws at the nose bridge. The second pair cracked in the same place within 18 months, despite handling them with extreme care (she only uses them for beach walks and driving, no sports). She says these are the most comfortable glasses she's ever owned, so for that they get 2 stars (her previous pair of Maui Jim's were Cyclone 136 which were heavy and uncomfortable). But when you pay this much for sunglasses they should last longer or be repaired without a runaround. When she bought the first pair at our local MJ retailer here in Hilton Head, I assumed the lenses were replaceable when I saw the screw mounts, which I found out was incorrect. After they broke, the seller offered the send them back to MJ for repair but the cost was prohibitive, and in my opinion should have been free anyway. But since they were so comfortable, I went ahead and got her another pair. But now that the second pair have the same 'defect', I will not waste another penny on Maui Jim's. Which is too bad because I know they are a quality brand, but I refuse to support a company that won't stand behind their product- especially after I gave them a second chance. And if you peruse the reviews here and elsewhere, you'll see this is not an isolated incident or due to counterfeit products. I'll probably try the sunglassfix replacement lens since we now have 2 perfectly good frames, and hopefully they'll last longer than the original lens. If not, here we come Tifosi.

column6: Skechers Performance Women's Go Walk 2 Slip-On Walking Shoe
column13: The Go Walk 2 are the ONLY shoes I can wear comfortably..
column14: I have Tarsal Tunnel Syndrome, Plantar Fasciitis, the beginning stages of hammer toes on both feet  and degenerative joint in my right foot.  The Go Walk 2 are the ONLY shoes I can wear comfortably...not that they take any of my discomfort away but they minimize my pain by allowing me to not antagonize the issues by virtue of having a very SOFT top (over my toes) thereby no rubbing, and they are a SHOE...which keeps me from having to grip with my toes to keep them on...like I do when wearing sandals...which I was doing year-round (Naots with the removable footbed).  One complaint...they've quit making the Go Walk 2 and NONE OTHER OF THE NEWER MODELS FIT THE SAME!  why couldn't they just have let well enough alone?!  The sizing is all wrong and while I wore a size 7 in these, now a 7 is too small and a 7 1/2 doesn't fit comfortably.  I've been buying up the Go Walk 2 wherever I can still FIND them! column6: Skechers Sport Men's Equalizer Persistent Slip-On Sneaker
column13: Good concept, less than stellar execution
column14:
This is Susan's son, first off; the shoes were purchased for me, so I felt it made sense for me to write the review. And, as a bit of a forewarning, I'm in the process of sending these back as I type this review because these shoes just did not work for me at all.

I found these in a local shoe store and really liked them when I tried them on, particularly the lightweight feel, but they didn't have a size that fit well, so we bought them on Amazon a half-size up later that day. They arrived August 12 and I've worn them repeatedly in the three days since. However, after wearing them and being on my feet for a few hours at a time, I've come to the conclusion that these shoes would only work for a relatively small niche of people; that is, people with narrow feet who live in cooler climates.

Below the mesh upper is another, relatively thick layer of fabric that negates any breathability the mesh upper might confer to the foot; add to this the synthetic covering of the memory foam insole and you have a recipe for a shoe that retains heat very well. While this may be a blessing in colder weather, in Texas heat, it's a veritable nightmare for your feet as, after less than an hour, your feet will be hot and sweaty and you'll be wanting to remove the shoes with all haste.

Normally, I love Skechers' memory foam insole, as my Avillos have it and I wore those until the insole started coming apart at the seams and flaking off (I got a good several years' use out of them, so I'd say I got my money's worth; they're still functional even now), but with the way the insole is designed on these Persistents, if you have anything but a very narrow foot or tend to walk on the outer edge of your foot, the memory foam insole might as well be nonexistent. I took a measurement and, at the arch of the foot on a size 11, the insole measures a measly 2 inches in width; for comparison, my own foot at the same spot is 3.5 inches wide. Granted, I have a wide foot, so that's not the best comparison, but I've generally found with Skechers that I can reliably go up a half-size if a wide is not available (and it wasn't in these in the color we bought) and be perfectly comfortable. Not so this time. I found the inside half of my foot was resting off the edge of the insole, which was not the most comfortable experience.

Nevertheless, these shoes DO have some good points. I said this shoe was a good concept with a less than stellar execution and I meant it. The idea of a lightweight, flexible, and casual slip-on shoe that you could wear with most anything is a very attractive one and in those respects, it actually succeeds. Skechers states on their website that a Men's 9 weighs about 6 or 7.5oz (I can't remember exactly) and I wouldn't be surprised if the 11 weighed more than 8-9oz; they are very flexible and the upper has a good amount of give that I've only found surpassed by Converse All-Stars High Tops. And they are also casual, looking good with shorts or jeans or cargo pants, though whether or not they would actually go with anything is dependent on color (the black or charcoal, I think, would work with just about any outfit, the latter especially).

However, because of the shortcomings of the stifling upper and the too narrow insole, the places you actually want a shoe to succeed (particularly a walking shoe), these fall far short of what I was hoping for them to be.so that's not the best comparison, but I've generally found with Skechers that I can reliably go up a half-size if a wide is not available (and it wasn't in these in the color we bought) and be perfectly comfortable. Not so this time. I found the inside half of my foot was resting off the edge of the insole, which was not the most comfortable experience.

Nevertheless, these shoes DO have some good points. I said this shoe was a good concept with a less than stellar execution and I meant it. The idea of a lightweight, flexible, and casual slip-on shoe that you could wear with most anything is a very attractive one and in those respects, it actually succeeds. Skechers states on their website that a Men's 9 weighs about 6 or 7.5oz (I can't remember exactly) and I wouldn't be surprised if the 11 weighed more than 8-9oz; they are very flexible and the upper has a good amount of give that I've only found surpassed by Converse All-Stars High Tops. And they are also casual, looking good with shorts or jeans or cargo pants, though whether or not they would actually go with anything is dependent on color (the black or charcoal, I think, would work with just about any outfit, the latter especially).

However, because of the shortcomings of the stifling upper and the too narrow insole, the places you actually want a shoe to succeed (particularly a walking shoe), these fall far short of what I was hoping for them to be.

column6: Men's Puma Super Cell Fusion Ice LE Golf Shoes
column14:
I love these golf shoes!

I purchased these shoes 3 years ago and decided to share my experience with these golf shoes.

I played High School golf so I had practice every day, 5 days a week, and often went golfing on the weekends with my family so I needed a reliable shoe that was comfortable and that could take a beating. These Puma golf shoes were the perfect find! The shoe fits as expected and they are extremely comfortable... often after a round of golf I would forget to take them off because they were so comfortable.

It's been 3 years and I still have these shoes and they are still in mint condition, no cracks, rips, or tears in any of the material and they look brand new. Even after playing golf in heavy rain and even snow! these shoes have stood the test of time and I strongly recommend them to anyone in need of a high quality golf shoe.

I will gladly buy another pair once I out grow or decide to replace my old pair.

Overall this is a great product and I'm very happy with my purchase!

column14:
Bought these for a tubing & rafting trip. I'd usually wear sandals (Chaco or Teva style) for something like this, but I wanted a closed toe for walking up the trails for the tubing.

My experience with Teva's shoes is they run true on width, but I usually go a 1/2 size up for the length.

I wore them around for a few days to make sure they would work for the amount of walking I'd be doing in them. The look is great and they are very comfortable, light and breathable for all day casual wear around town. They worked well with socks and without.

From a technical point of view, they drained & dried pretty well for a water/rafting shoe. Way more comfortable than water shoes that are just a mesh sock with a rubberized bottom. Better on the toes when you lock your feet into the raft on the rapids and kept the feet a little warmer than sandals.

Overall very impressed. These won't replace my sandals or hiking shoes/boots, but they are a great in-between shoe and light enough to justify their inclusion in my pack.

column6: Crocs Unisex Baya Clog
column14:
I was given a pair of these by my wife, and they became my go-to shoes for wearing while doing yard work. Insanely comfortable, easy to hose off to clean, great ventilation on hot Southern days. They stayed outside for me to wear when the next impromptu chore came along. I had them for over a year, wore them constantly when yard duties called each weekend.

Lately, I noticed as I placed the shoes on my feet each week that they were getting harder and harder to slide on my feet. I was finally forcing my feet into the toe box just to get them on. I worried that I was retaining water in my feet, possibly a sign of heart issues...turns out, all I needed was a new pair. The shoes, left outside day after day, will slowly shrink. My old and new shoes, side-by-side, show the old to be easily one size smaller than it first was, maybe two sizes. The new shoes, by contrast, are roomy and comfortable.

[In the attached photo, the shoe on the left is the "old" shoe, the one on the right is the one just delivered, and BOTH are size 11]

The moral to the story is to care for your Crocs, don't leave them outside for days on end. Otherwise, they may begin to get snug on you, too.

column13: too narrow and NO arch support
column14: i normally wear a 9A or 9.5AA. AA is never too narrow for me, and about 30% of the time, AA is a bit too wide (ex: I have 1 other pair of Trotters, size 9.5AA, whose straps are a little too wide).  I can wear medium shoes only if the footbed isn't too wide and they have fully adjustable straps, and even then sometimes the overall shape of the straps and shoe is too wide. i ordered the Grace in a 9.5AA and - surprise! - they are a bit too narrow in the forefoot to be comfortable. I can only remember once in my life (and i am old and have always bought a lot of shoes, ha) that i have run across a size narrow shoe that is too narrow for me. these might have stretched enough and i got such a good deal that i probably would have tried that, except that the arch support in this shoe is so non-existent that it makes a sucking sound at the arch of my foot when i walk. I had to laugh. You know how some shoes have discernable arch support - that is, the arch part of the shoe rises up?  Well, in this shoe it caves in at the arch.  (i have medium-high arches and have to add slight to medium arch supports if i want to avoid knee pain in all shoes except for Dansko, Cobb Hill and some Eccos and Romikas.)

column13: My husband is always losing or breaking his and this pair is his favorite style of sunglasses
column14:
I was very excited to receive these sunglasses in the mail. My husband is always losing or breaking his and this pair is his favorite style of sunglasses. They have a silver frame with green earpieces. The lenses have a colorful mirrored finish.

The frame of these sunglasses are a half frame supporting the lenses from the top. They feel like they are well built, I don't feel like they will fall apart in my hands or his. The nose piece has two soft silicone pads that flex independently of each other allowing a comfortable fit on the bridge of the nose.

I like that when he looks downward to do something, the glasses do not slip off of his face. It is also nice that the arms rest gently on the ears so they do not pull or tug on your ears. These sunglasses are very nice looking, they would be a great gift or an extra pair to keep in your spouse's car. My husband really likes this pair and I think he will be wearing them for quite some time. I received this product for free in exchange for my honest, unbiased review.

column13: Shoes are knock off from real Gentle Souls Brand
column14: I believe these shoes are a knock off of the real gentle souls brand.  The pair of shoes I recieved had bad quality control.  The arch support in one of the shoes had a smaller stitching which created a larger pad in the arch then the other.  Because of that the arch padding sticks up too much making these shoes are unwearable.  Also, I have 2 pairs of these shoes that I bought from Nordstroms at $195 so when I saw these for around $80 on Amazon I thought 'score'! But I was wrong the logo is not the same logo as the ones from Nordstroms.  I also found the top strap to be too tight on both the shoes from Nordstroms and these so I actually just cut it off which created a really nice pair of ballet flats.  With that being said I tried these on briefly when I received them to ensure fit and promptly cut the strap off.  I wasn't until I went to wear them out one day that I discovered the arch issue, so now I can't return them.

column13: So happy I found these shoes- I needed ones with a ...
column14: So happy I found these shoes- I needed ones with a steel toe but they're almost impossible to find in a women's 5. These are a great alternative to bulky ankle boots. Fit great out of the box, didn't need to be broken in. I did, however, end up buying gel insoles (heels only because they don't make insoles small enough for a size 5!) because these weren't comfortable for 16 hour days. I've worn these so often and for such long hours at a time that I have calluses on my toe knuckles from the steel. That may be a con for some but it hasn't really bothered me. I expect at least two year's wear from these, definitely worth the money.  UPDATE July 2017: Two years later, still love these shoes. I did have to replace the laces once because one got torn and broke, but they've held up alright. There is one hole on the outside of the shoe, but I've never had an issue with dirt/moisture getting in. Replacing because I'm starting a new job and treating myself. For the amount of hours I spend in these, I'm more than willing to replace these every 2 years.

column6: Fabuxry Women's Casual Shoulder Bags Zipper Nylon Messenger Handbags
column14:
I have A LOT of these handbags, and I mean A LOT! This is one of the nicer ones because (1) decent price and comes in gray, (2) the zippers match the bag instead of the giant pale gray zippers frequently used on every bag color to save money, (3) holds a lot without looking like luggage, the bottom of this bag measures 11.25" X 4.25" and it arrived much much sooner than promised. No problem with the lining getting caught in the zippers either.
Now you should know that this is not a designer bag. It seems to be sewn "well enough", however, the front flap is slightly crooked as is the zipper on that flap. (People who would be bothered by this, probably aren't buying inexpensive bags from China.) Like all nylon bags, it wipes up easily with a damp cloth. The pockets are large, even the one on the face of the flap and the one on the back. Not overly crazy about the big zipper pulls, but that's not a deal breaker. The handle strap is highly woven nylon, not that loosely woven cotton that looks "ratty" after a while. All said, I am pleased with it enough to want it in other colors.

column14:
I needed some hiking boots for my trip to Utah. I stomped around Arches, Capitol Reef, Zion and Bryce Canyon for over a week in these, and couldn't be happier. The average amount of hiking I did per day was about 5 miles, mostly moderate in difficulty (though I did tackle some of the shorter challenging hikes, like The Delicate Arch and The Upper Emerald Pool,) and my feet felt fine (100+ degree heat, more than anything, was the limiting factor.) The traction was better than expected, and the support these shoes provided exceeded my expectations.

Over all, these hikers are light weight, supportive and comfortable. Best of all, you can find them for <$70 new. Highly recommended.

column6: FRYE Women's Jamie Ring Tall Western Boot
column13: ... these after looking for YEARS for a pair of nice leather boots with a decent sole that wasn't just ...
column14:
I purchased these after looking for YEARS for a pair of nice leather boots with a decent sole that wasn't just a picture of wood wrapped around the heel. I was excited to find these and at such a good price. I tried them on and noticed several things. See pictures.

Pro:
- The calf width is perfect for me (5ft. 7 inches, 120 lbs). It isn't as wide as most boots which is a good thing..minimal gapping.
- The color was nice.
- The height was perfect.

Con:
- The Leather is super super stiff. It is thicker than my other leather boots which is nice, but I am now wondering how long it will take to break these
babies in.
- The ankle section is nearly impossible to get your foot in. Once you do, it is so stiff you can hardly move your ankle. That said, once they are on, they make you look like you have cankles due to the thickness of the leather and the cut. There is no seam in the front of the boot so the leather isn't fitted in the front potion of your ankle.
- I thought these were made in the US. They aren't. They are made in Mexico? So why the super expensive price? There is a nice big stamp right inside the boot with "Made in Mexico". Sigh. Also, I think someone else either wore these or at least tried them on because the inside leather of the boot was worn.

I still haven't decided if I want to keep them yet or not. I want to love them, but I fear I won't and then will be irritated that I spent this much $$ on a pair of boots I don't actually love.

column13: I'm from Australia and was looking for a better quality boot than is on offer over here
column14:
I'm from Australia and was looking for a better quality boot than is on offer over here, so after reading through countless reviews I settled on these.....
Even though I'm a fairly big guy I don't have a wide foot, so I was pretty surprised to find how tight across the toe box these boots are, especially compared to my last couple of pairs of old boots that are all compsite toe and same size. I'd definitely go a wider size if I was to buy them again. Also the standard insoles are very thin in the forefoot area so it feels like your walking on bare concrete. The finish on the outside of the boot wasn't quite as high quality as I expected from wolverine. Other than that the heel and ankle support is awesome.
Not the best but still a good boot overall.

column6: Salomon Women's Speedcross 3 Trail Running Shoe
column14: I waited a long time to get a pair of these shoes. They are pricey if you don't get them on sale. I got a good deal because it was a hideous color that apparently didn't sell well. After I got them, I realized they weren't as ugly as I thought. Anyhoo, they are a bit narrower than my previous trail shoe and I was worried about not feeling as stable, but they are actually very stable. Of course, the  super aggressive sole is great on just about everything except wet wood and slippery rocks, but really, what shoe is good on those surfaces? I like technical trails with lots of rocks (dry ones), roots, twists and quick up/downs. These shoes are great for this terrain. If you want a shoe to wear to the mall or walking your local greenway, I don't recommend them. You will throw away good money as the soles will wear out super fast on hard surfaces. If you want an aggressive, light shoe that you can run or hike trails in, then this is your shoe! :)

column6: Hammer Anvil RFID Blocking Minimalist Genuine Leather Slim Front Pocket Wallet
column14: Lots of slots for lots of cards.  One nice aspect is that, with slots on both sides, this is a good card case for left-handed people.  Maybe you other lefties out there carry your wallets differently than me, but my last small wallet had card slots on only one side, and I would slide it into my right back pocket with the cards towards me and the slot openings up.  When I would pull it out of the pocket, the thing would be upside down.  If I put it in my pocket with the cards away from me and the outer slots up, it would come out of the pocket right side up but with the cards on the side away from me.  With this case, it will come out of either back pocket right-side up with your most-used cards on the side that faces you.  But if you are going to use it as a wallet, be aware that you are going to get *maybe* seven bills folded in half in the middle slot, and you might have to take the cards out to let the case be flexible enough to get the bills in.

Granted, I do not wear extremely high end shoes with lots of padding and support built into them. These soles have helped so much already in the first few weeks that I have been using them. column6: KEEN Men's Newport H2 Sandal
column13: Nice shoe, questionable quality, even worse warranty -- one month in and I'm waiting to see if I get a replacement
column14: The shoe fits tightly (which is good for support) and as such you need to pull it onto your foot. That means the straps on the front and the back come into play pretty much every time you put them on. The strap on my right shoe broke after 35 days, which means I can't send it back to Amazon. Instead I have to deal with the Keen warranty department, which is very slow. They want pictures and detailed product information, which is not readily available on the Amazon invoice. For example, they want a product code on a little plastic sticker that fell off the shoes after about a week of wearing them. So now I have a pretty expensive one-month-old shoe that is nearly impossible to put on my foot and am told I'll need to wait 15 work days to have my claim processed. They can then either send me a replacement pair (which I *hope* they will) *OR* send me a voucher. But here's the kicker: the voucher is for the amount I paid on Amazon (a little over eighty bucks) but can only be used on the Keen website (where this shoe costs over a hundred bucks + shipping). It's unclear whether they'll make me mail back the broken shoes. Anyway, not a great experience so far with this company. Hopefully I'll hear back from them soon and they'll agree to send me a replacement pair of shoes quickly.

column6: Vionic with Orthaheel Technology Women's Relax Luxe Slipper
column14: I have extreme pain in my feet from wearing flip flops almost everyday for the last 12 years. I have developed plantar fasciitis and it can be very hard to walk some days.  I did a ton of research on different orthotic companies to buy a pair of shoes from and Vionic seemed to have the best most consistent reviews. I was very hopeful when I purchased these slippers but I honestly did not think that they would work as good as some said, because after everything I have tried to relieve the pain, nothing has worked. I figured that these would be a bit of a wider slipper based on the reviews.  As soon as these arrived I tried them on. I could instantly feel pressure relieved from my heel. The arch of my foot did hurt a bit, but I think that is because I am so used to wearing flat shoes with zero support. I work them for a few hours then took them off and tried to walk around barefoot, boy oh boy did I instantly feel the difference. I could immediately feel the pain rushing back into my heel. These slippers are wider, but I prefer them that way so no complaints from me.  If you are like me and considering buying something to help out with foot pain, please do yourself a favor and purchase these. If they worked for me, I'm almost certain they can help you.  Updated: I've had these for a few days now and have worn them the entire day for the last two days. I honestly have noticed such a huge difference in the pain. It's not 100% gone, more like 75% better than what it was.

column6: Rainbow Sandals Women's 2 Tone Leather Double Stack Wide Strap, Classic Mocha, Size 10 (11.25\)"
column13: Wear them in the shower to mold to your feet quickly
column14:
So when you open the box and slip these on, they'll be hard, tight and you'll wonder why you bought them. But don't panic! Once they mold to your feet they're incredible. Wearing them in the shower a few times does wonders to speed up the process (I did wipe them dry after just in case the water would damage them, but I've also worn them in the rain since then with no issues so I really wouldn't worry about it)

Yes they still seem expensive when you could probably buy fairly comfortable flip flops for $5, but more than comfort you're really paying for quality. I wore them for months and months while working abroad in some pretty crappy terrain, and through it all not a single stitch came loose. Meanwhile, I had a few pairs of cheap (albeit comfortable) flip flops with me and not a single pair lasted more than two weeks. The Rainbows not only lasted me the rest of the trip, but they're still the only flip flops I wear.

When these fall apart (in a decade I'm guessing?) I will definitely buy another pair.

column6: Belvah Quilted Floral Hipster Crossbody Handbag
column14: This crossbody bag is absolutely perfect!  I bought it to carry to meetings and when I serve at church because I have terrible migraines and need to have my medication handy at all times.  I was tired of hauling around a large purse or bag but wanted something I could keep on my person.  I looked at some more expensive Vera Bradley bags in a similar style and pattern but did not want to pay upward of $50.  I decided to give this bag a try as it is just as cute and much more economical.  It is perfect to hold two of my migraine shots (complete with their accompanying boxes), a small wallet, a few cosmetics and a phone; all of a woman's necessities!  The strap is very long and adjustable so you could use it on your shoulder as well as crossbody.  The strap is thick enough that it does not cut into your shoulders during wear.  There is a small outside pocket that zips and an inside pocket that zips as well as two pouch-like pockets on the inside that are edged with elastic.  The bag appears to be washable if need be, although I have not tried this and am not sure how the bow would fair in the wash.  This bag is small enough not to be obtrusive or bulky but large enough to carry your necessities.  I definitely recommend this bag!

column6: Kenneth Cole New York Men's Double Header LE Fashion Sneaker
column14: These shoes, are AWESOME!!! I just have to say that. The Tobacco color is detailed. It's perfect. I only have one issue, the shoe strings seem to be made out of a thin fragile leather, and rip in half very easily with a few ties. So, what I would suggest is that you leave the shoe tied permanently and use the zipper to get in and out of your shoe, because it would seem that the leathery shoe strings are just for show, or you could just buy some nice shoe strings that would go great with these shoes, other than that I have no complaints.  P.S. I don't know if this has happened to anyone else, but it would appear that you have to sign for these shoes once they are delivered. It's a good thing I was home because the U.S. Postal woman began knocking on my door, and usually they just knock once to let you know you have a package. So, I looked out my peephole and I saw her begin to leave with my pacakge so I had to catch her before she left, and she had me sign for them. I thought that was interesting because I never had to sign for shoes or clothes or really anyting besides electronics, like a computer, laptop or a cell phone. Maybe it's because the shoes are considered up scale and are a bit pricey; I'm not sure, all I have to say is make sure your home when you order these specific shoes.

These shoes seem like they'll last me a long time and seem to fit as expected (I wear a size 9 in just about every brand of shoe, and a size 9 in these fit me perfect). column14:
When I opened the box I'm pretty happy. And then the laser lady looked initially. I thought they were really cute, and exactly what I wanted.

Looking more closely at them, I was a little disappointed. There is this white dish around the wedge heel, and although it's nice very bright, it's still there. It's a little annoying and I tried to clean it off but it is not at all.

I put them on just to see if I could maybe do with it and walked around in them for a few minutes. They are a little big, so they slip off as my heel whenever I am walking, so that's really annoying. But what's even worse, it digs any to my ankle bone online and even after wearing them for only five minutes, I had that red mark. I'm pretty sure every woman knows exactly what I'm talking about.

They really are cute, and I hate to send them back because I don't know if getting a smaller size is even going to fix it. I may have to talk to you as a company just to see if they have any thoughts on it.

For the price, it's not a horrible pair of shoes. - the fact that there's the white film, and they dig into my ankle. If I put a insert into them, maybe they will fit a little bit better, but I just don't know if I want to do all that.

column13: The best part, they NEVER go out of style

My husband wears them daily (we live in Florida) and when they get to the point where the sole under his big toe is wearing down, I buy him a new pair (once a year).  These shoes are durable and if you're trying to get past spending over $50 on flip flops, just remember they will last at least a year if you wear them daily. column13: A very comfortable multi-use waterproof boot
column14: I really like the boots.  These appear more rugged than my first Muck boots that had a very soft sole which wore out quickly from "non-skid" on boat decks and the beige color stained.  I bought them to primarily wear when saltwater fishing in the Pacific off  the So Calif and Mexican coast. ( Taking them to the snow or mud would be a second purpose.) I often fish from party boats and the decks are frequently awash in saltwater hose spray rinsing away bait pieces, tuna blood,  etc, and less often in splashes of saltwater wave-spray.  These are high enough to keep me dry and the foot bed is stable enough to keep my footing.  They are easy on/off.  I recently finished a 5-day trip wearing these all day while fishing (rubber sandals when not fishing) and with fresh socks each day I had no foot problems.  These are "keepers."

US	52811582	R1SDEY0FLBWSK6	B00HG9QDUO	72053683	KEEN Men's Tyretread WP Chelsea Boot	Shoes	5	2	2	N	Y	Was Hesitant To Buy, But So Glad I Did	Somehow I got this far in life having never owned a pair of boots with no laces or zipper, but I really liked these and wanted to give them a shot. I have owned lots of Keens and have never been disappointed- plus they always fit right. So if I were going to try a "Chelsea" pull-on boot, it made sense to start with a brand I knew and trusted. I ordered the same 9.5(D) size as all my Keens and waited for the box to show up on my porch (which happened the very NEXT day even though I just used my usual Prime shipping- Amazon logistics are incredible!!). First: I wasn't sure what texture the (black) leather would be. The description lists "full grain leather" (which means slick & polished in the case of Keen NoPo's two versions), but based on the pictures it could go either way. I was pleased to find that they are somewhere in the middle of the texture spectrum (smooth but not polished) and really solid looking with that thick sole and aggressive tread. They seemed a little loose when I tried them on, but when I added the Sof Sole insole that I always use, they were nice and snug. The first several days I wore them around the house for a few hours in the evenings to be sure I didn't need to return them (another great Amazon feature) and they quickly passed. That weekend I gave them the real world test doing errands, a night out, Mass on Sunday and lots of walking during a picnic in the park. I couldn't be more pleased- comfortable, not too heavy, no ankle rubbing, snug fit and great looking in their simplicity! I don't notice any of the left/right sizing imbalance issues mentioned by some reviewers (which had made me a little hesitant to order these), but that may just be good luck if it's a production issue. So now that I'm sure these work-- and do so better than I even hoped, I believe I'll keep an eye on the "peanut" color price or maybe switch over to the laced version for that. I'm very pleased and would recommend these without hesitation. I hope this helps anyone pondering the purchase!hope this helps anyone pondering the purchase!	2015-08-16

column13: Nice but not durable and slippery
column14:
I liked my old Nautilus so much I had bought 3 so far. This was my 4th and I went for a more formal (meeting) style.

Unfortunately these are disappointing. Like the other ones, they aren't very durable. The last pairs lasted less than a year and these won't last beyond that. Already cracking severely at the bends.

The worst part is they slip on wet and oily conditions. This is almost as important as being steel toe. In my entire career I may have slipped 3 times. Since wearing these I have slipped more than 3 times and have to walk around.

The last thing I'll say is these were slightly tighter and breaking them in is taking very long.

I would not recommend but they are 3 stars because they are still better than other brands (doc marten, wolverine).

column14: I bought these as my first pair of hiking boots for a trip to Montana.  I really didn't know what I was looking for and I relied heavily on the positive reviews when I decided to go with a pair of these. I was not disappointed.  Keep in mind, as other people have said, they do run a big large.  I'm normally a size 10 and I went with a 9.5 which worked pretty well.  (Keep in mind you'll want to be wearing somewhat thick socks and your feet do swell with physical activity).  My Ariats received a lot of rough wear during my trip (40 miles of very steep hiking in a week) but they held up very well.  I just walked to work a couple times to break them in before the trip (two 4 mile walks) and got a few small blisters here and there (as you can expect with any long hikes).  They are extremely light weight.  The package they arrived in weighed 3 lbs total, box and boots included.  I could not believe how light they were.  One small complaint: they don't breathe very well.  This didn't pose any huge problems to me during my trip, but I did notice my feet getting very warm while I was first breaking them in.  Honestly though, it's a small flaw in the light of a solid pair of boots for a very decent price.  Go for it.

column6: Scarpa Men's R-Evolution GTX Hiking Boot
column13: Nevertheless - the fit was very good - no blisters at all - none - despite ...
column14: I ordered 4 different boots to compare fit and features and chose these boots over the other three.  Then I decided to go with these new boots on our annual 9 day 130 mile backpack trip into the Paysaten Wilderness in Northern Washington rather than my old pair - for fit reasons (my old boots seem to have become too small).  I'd only had these boots a week and hiked about 4 miles in them before the backpack trip.  So no break in was done.  Nevertheless - the fit was very good - no blisters at all - none - despite the long days in the boots.  The boots are light weight - yet the support was fine.  They seemed to wear well - but it is hard to be completely certain after only130 miles.  The soles have a  good rubber composition - it is a more "sticky" rubber that the other boots I tried or my old boots.  This was a great feature when scrambling several rock peaks along the trip.  The "stickiness" of the rubber did not seem to affect wear - the wear was pretty minimal after this trip - comparable to my other boots on previous trips of similar length. I stepped in the river to pull out a fellow hiker who had slipped off a log - one boot filled completely with water.  I drained the water and changed socks and by the end of the day, some 6 hours later, the boot was dry - I was surprised. I think these boots dry more quickly than several of my older pairs of Asolo boots.  The Gore Tex worked well - we had one day of light rain and it had rained heavily overnight and the vegetation was wet adjacent the trail.  Then the same day I slipped off a slippery rock while getting water and stepped into the shallow creek.  Nonetheless - my feet stayed dry.  I think these boots are better in this area than my last two Asolo pairs which are also Gore Tex.  (Not all Gore Tex is created equal-- it works better in some boots than others - for some reason).  However - this year's rain day was not as bad as the last three years have been on this Paysaten trip - so I can't sayfor sure that these boots are better as far as water resistance.  My only rather minor criticism is the lacing.  The lacing hooks are a little difficult to catch with the laces - one has to watch carefully or you will find that you've only partially seated the lace in the hook.  I can do my old Asolo boots while half asleep and the same with the Asolo and Lowa boots I tried as comparison when I ordered these boots.  So Scarpa could do better there - talk to your engineers....  But this is a mild annoyance.  Also - the laces are rather thin and probably will have to be replaced after a year or so - and often I can get 3+ years from a pair of laces.  Overall - I think these are a nice pair of boots - well worth the price - and very comfortable with no break in time - and I really like the sticky rubber of the soles.

column6: Otter Wax Heat-Activated Fabric Dressing | 1/2 Pint | All-Natural Water Repellent | Made in USA
column13: OK if you don't mind the mess
column14: Bought this in 2014 but just tried using it.  All I can say is - it is messy!  Heated the can as directed in a small pot of water, it melted OK.  But getting it out of the can while it is melted (ie hot) is difficult - I used a paint brush about 1-1/2 inches wide, it was hard to get it into & out of the can.  If you use a narrower brush you won't pick up as much wax.  Another problem - I waited until it was an 80+ degree day, had to work inside though because that's where my stove is.  Couldn't take the stuff outside because the water wouldn't stay hot enough to keep the wax melted.  Another problem - as soon as the brush hit the wax & I started to apply it to the jacket (Barbour waxed cotton), the wax began to harden.  Tried heating the wax (on the jacket) with my hair drier - that worked somewhat.  Even with the 80+ degree heat, it wax started to harden up on the jacket.  Then tried using an old washcloth to dip into the can - that worked better than the brush, but it was messy also.  Best method was to heat the jacket, in small patches of course, WHILE applying the wax from the washcloth - because I could heat not only the cloth but the wax on the cloth also, at the same time.  There are still patches of wax in spots, now hanging the jacket in the hot sun and going to wipe it in/down with another lint free cloth.  I always wanted a Barbour waxed cotton jacket & saved up for it. Next time I am saving up to have the jacket waxed by the company!  Not worth the mess!  There is enough wax in the can to do my entire jacket (hip length) but I only did the shoulders, arms and just past the pockets on the front and most of the back.  There is enough wax left in the can to do the rest of the jacket.

column13: ... few other pairs of Clarks shoes which I've really liked (mostly dressy/casual shoes for work which are really comfy)
column14:
I've owned a few other pairs of Clarks shoes which I've really liked (mostly dressy/casual shoes for work which are really comfy). So I thought I'd try these loafers. A couple of thoughts if you're considering:

- I like the look. Casual, but subtle and classy. They look especially good with jeans.
- These loafers aren't really navy blue. To me, they really look gray with a hint of blue. Maybe Cool Gray is the right thing to call them.
- These don't seem to have the really nice, cushy bottoms like my other Clarks. It's okay, but not pillowy soft.
- The suede is a pain to clean, and I gave up. I spilled some water on them, and I could never really get the stains out. I tried a few of the different methods suggested online, but none really worked completely. So now these shoes rarely get worn.

So, If you're okay with suede and the color gray, then these aren't too bad.

column14: I looked at so many RFID wallets and finally decided on this one.  I LOVE it!  It holds everything I need, is attractive and fits in my purse.  I like the way it's 'trifold'--I put my credit cards in the center part so it's extra safe.  The only drawback I could possibly see in this wallet is that the place where you put change is zippered.  I've always carried the French style of wallet where the place you put change is secured by metal pieces (sorry, I don't know how to describe it!).  Anyway, that's not really important to me anymore because I only carry a few quarters for emergencies---these days I use either paper dollars or the credit card.  As for the RFID protection, I tried some of those little sleeves that you insert into the slots in your wallet.  They are made basically of paper with a thin foil-like liner.  I bought 4 of them at a local store for $10.  That was not a wise buy.  Within a week, the sleeve was getting crinkled and worn when I pulled out my credit card.  I wouldn't recommend those sleeves.  Rather, just buy a wallet like this one and ALL your cards (including your drivers license) will be protected!

column6: Reef Men's Phantom Speed Logo Flip-Flop
column13: Great sandal at a decent price
column14:
Just got my Reefs today...On Sunday believe it or not. They started Sunday delivery out here in the sticks of central Illinois. GO AMAZON !!!

These sandals are very comfortable and decently priced. It is always a gamble buying shoes or sandals-flip-flops online. I wear a 10 1/2 and ordered an 11. They fit perfectly with no room to spare. If I were to order them again I would order an 11 1/2. The heel of my foot does not overhang the sandal but it is very close. I would say my heel is exactly even with the back of the sandal. I wear a wide shoe more because of aged joints than necessarily a wide foot. There is no room to spare on the width either. I did not see any way to order a wider flip-flop from them though. The arch support seems very good and they were comfortable the first time I put them on. Initially they did not seem to be very grippy. They were kind of slippery on my linoleum floor. but after an hour or so of wearing them they started to grip the ground better. They are very lightweight, look good, and appear to be well made. All in all I would buy them again. Just note that you must order a full size bigger than your normal size, and they probably will not fit a person with a wide foot.

column6: The North Face Ultra 109 GTX Running Shoe Men's
column14:
Got these shoes as a Christmas gift. Had the model before and loved them, so I asked for these, and was disappointed in them. First off, the insoles were paper thin to start with, and I shredded them within the first 2 months. Replaced with combat boot insoles and carried on. However, within 3 months, the outside edge of the toe cup (right where it says "North Face") had cut a hole into the mesh of the shoe, that degraded extremely quickly and now pokes through to my sock (compromising any water resistance they may have held.)

The shoes overall are fairly comfortable once you replace the insoles, so it is a crying shame to give them such a low review. But for $110 shoes, they have lasted less than half a year with regular use (not even heavy duty camping/trail running) and beyond that, they are slick as snot once you get into any wet tile or linoleum floors, not to mention that I have nearly lost a front tooth when I slipped on a rock as I was crossing a stream. Sole lugs provide great traction in mud and dirt, but will betray you as soon as you set foot on any smooth surfaces. Would not buy again at this price.

column13: Narrow as usual, but comfy and dry.
column14: Many Clark's boots seem to run narrow. I normally wear an 8, or 8.5 with thick socks, but this size 9 works best for me. I needed the larger size for the width in the toe, and use an insole to make the rest of it it fit better. I have high arches, so nothing ever feels like 'good arch support' to me, but the ankle support serves to resist my ankle pronation rather well. They are flexible, nicely waterproof, and easy-on-easy-off, so they've become my 'go-to' dog-walking shoes for wet grass or cool days. A bit sweaty, as I'd expect from waterproof shoes, but comfy otherwise. I've had them for a year, and although I don't wear them every day, and seldom all day, I wear them often and they've held up well. column6: ACORN Kid's Colby Gore Moc  Slipper(Infant-Toddler-Little Kid-Big Kid)
column14: After reading all the other reviews on this brand of slipper, I was nervous about them being too small as so many other customers complained about. I did not have this experience at all. My daughter wears a size 3 1/2 tennis shoe which leaves a thumb's width of growning room at the big toe. I ordered these slippers in size 3/4 and they fit well enough to stay on her feet but are big enough that they will fit her until she is truly a size 4. I always replace my daughter's shoes before her toes reach the very end and I don't necessarily go by what the foot measuring tool at the shoe store reads. Instead I see what she feels most comfortable walking in. Her foot is also very wide at the toes. I don't know if this approach is why I had better results but I'm very happy with the slippers. I actually bought her 2 different styles of these slippers, one pair did not have elastic at the sides. One pair is for school & one is for home. The only difference between the two is the pair with elastic at the sides are a little wider around her foot. If your child has a very narrow foot you might want to look at the styles without elastic sides. As far as quality and appearance these are the best made and cutest slippers that are actually functional that I've found. I am extremely happy with my purchase and am glad I did not let the negative reviews keep me from buying them. I hope this review is helpful as far as determining what size and style to buy for your child.

column6: I SKI Delirium Aviator Sunglasses
column13: The ISKI Sunglass brand is back!
column14:
I recently bought the 'Delirium Aviator' & the 'Pallavicini' models of the iSKi sunglasses, & for cheap @ $7.00/pr., & they are decent enough. Although I do own an older original model of iSki sunglasses bought in CO back around 2000, probably for around $15. And the older model (no actual model name listed on the sunglass frame) has very nice Rose-Colored Lens in them, tinted more heavily on the top & bottom portion of the lens. Naturally, the Rose Tinting accentuates and intensifies most colors, which is very pleasant. Neither the Delirium of Palla frames are exactly the preferred shape of my originals, but fairly close. My originals had sort of that traditional Aviator lens shape, (in plastic frames) but less tear-dropped shaped, more flattened on the bottom, giving them a slightly smaller frame & lens. I have loved my original iSKI's & have always been afraid of losing or breaking them, which is why I took a chance and bought these newer models of the ISKI brand. And the new models do have the Silver/Reflective lens as do the old models, I like the fact that these iSKI sunglasses don't have those wrap-around frames which gives me the look of a glassy-eyed outer-space alien, one of those Greys. I prefer the old school RayBan frame styles, which these have.

My only complaint about +90% of the sunglasses traditionally found on Sunglass Racks is that they rarely offer any sunglasses with darker tinted lens. My eyes are sensitive to very bright sunlight, and if I am skiing, the snow is extremely bright at times & hurts my eyes with most models of sunglasses. Luckily, I have found a couple pairs of truly dark lens sunglasses and revert to using those on blindingly sunny days. Right now I just use the iSKI models for driving, if it is not terrifically bright & sunny.

I have a pair of sunglasses that I got for free with some product long ago, they are called 'Happy Cat' sunglasses w/smiling cat face on one stem, & the trademark "Twins" on the other ear stem, and these Happy Cat's have the some of the darkest lens I have ever used, but they are truly perfect for sun bleached days. Although the Happy Cat sunglasses look like kid's sunglasses, one stem bright yellow, the other stem white, the frame red. These TWIN Happy Cats were made in Taiwan, I wish I could find another pair......

I also have a pair of Italian made sunglasses, made by L.G.R. (Freetown model I believe?), that were given to me by a friend who said the lenses (dark greenish tint) were way too dark for him, but they are perfect for me in harsh sunlight. However, the TWIN 'Happy Cats' actually have an even darker tint, grey.

I sort of wish the new owners of ISKI made some models with darker lens tints, and maybe sturdier frames, I know I would be willing to pay more for darker lenses, mirroring not necessary, in mostly traditionally shaped frames. But naturally, pleasing everyone when it comes to sunglasses is impossible. Certain shape sunglass frames just go right with certain face shapes. Determine what looks best, and feels best for you and stick with that shape, but too each their own. There are certainly some wild-ass sunglasses out there these days, and some people look pretty good in them, but not everyone can successfully pull it off, but it doesn't stop them from trying.

Since sunglasses often have to take a beating, I have lost or broken so many over the years, that I refuse to pay Big Bucks for sunglasses anymore, and these new iSKI's at $7 are a good bang for the buck. ISKI has down some inventive frame color combos which are fun.
I'd just like some darker tinted lenses, with maybe lens color choices in grey, green, rose/red, purple, & blue....is that asking too much? Probably. Oh well. Hard to go too wrong for $7; but I'd pay more for the aforementioned options.ins" on the other ear stem, and these Happy Cat's have the some of the darkest lens I have ever used, but they are truly perfect for sun bleached days. column13: My favorite boot.  Sizing is very small.  Heel cup takes getting used-to. Still not zero drop.  Otherwise awesome!
column14: I wear 11-1/2 W Belleville Flight Boots, but the TR103s were too small in size 12W, so I returned them and got 13W.  They are awesome.  The sole is flexible enough to roll it up in your hand, but tough enough to protect your feet from rough ground.  I would only point out two areas for improvement:  As has been commented on, the heel cup is unusually stiff around the achilles tendon.  It is made of several layers of leather, and it feels uncomfortable until you break them in, and even then they feel odd when you first put them on.  I wear Vermont Darn Tough Wool boot socks, so it doesn't bother me, but I haven't tried them for a long ruck.  I wear them everyday for 12 Hours plus, but I'm in an office job.  The second minor gripe is that they have a 2mm heel drop.  Yeah, I know, that's less than 1/10th of an inch, but when I switch from my Minimus running shoes, I notice it.  I will switch to a true zero-drop boot as soon as one is available.  In the meantime, this is my favorite.

column6: KEEN Women's Clearwater CNX Sandal
column13: Great for a multi-day canoe trip
column14: I bought these shoes for a multi-day canoe trip, and they did not disappoint! Even though I had never broken them in, they were comfortable right from the start. They were perfect for getting in and out of water and walking on rocky surfaces. I even like the little reflector tags so you can spot them quickly with a flashlight outside your tent at night. You can cinch them up very tightly if walking in muck. My only wish is that they dried a little faster, but really, I can't imagine any shoe of this type would dry any faster than these would. All in all, they seem very well built, and I hope they last me for many river trips to come! They are also nice enough for wearing around town.

column6: Striker™ II GTX® Side Zip Uniform Boots
column14:
I had a pair of Striker 2 boots that I bought about 4 or 5 years ago and they lasted about that long, and I still use them to go to the range and other things. They have held up great to this day, they just don't hold a shine anymore so I decided to get a new pair of duty boots. There was a slight problem with the zipper on one of the boots, it would unzip but if I tied the laces around the top of the boot there was no problem - I just had to tie them instead of using the zippers. This zipper issue started after about two or three years of patrol use in Alaska. No complaints there.

I was so pleased with Striker 2's that I bought another pair. I noticed that the zippers on the model had changed. This zipper broke after one or two days. There has obviously been some cost cutting going on and it is very apparent when you compare the pair of boots I had first to the new ones. When I buy Danner boots I expect to pay a couple hundred dollars and get five years of them.

I would not buy another pair of these boots. I will be going with the non-zippers. I don't know if the durability of zipper boots is just not a feasible thing or if these are just cheap, but I would not recommend them.

I don't know if I'm just unlucky or if Dr. Martens quality is just dropping. However I can no longer wear these for fear of completely ripping the sole lengthwise.

column6: Merrell Men's Jungle Leather Slip-On Shoe
column13: These are better than my flip-flops!
column14: I have a pair of these shoes that are very comfortable. By way of background, I have "funny-shaped" size 12 feet that don't feel comfortable in most shoes. I am also a bit arthritic, which makes tying shoelaces a little difficult. As a result, I wear flip-flops for most of the year, both because they are comfortable and because they are easy to put on and to remove. The biggest drawbacks of my flip-flop habit are that I live in the Northwest (which means my feet get cold or wet in the fall and winter), and that the open toes don't provide any protection against hazards on the ground.  I was amazed to discover that these shoes fit well. They are snug, but not tight. Even better, they are easy to put on by simply putting my foot in and wiggling it a bit. I am able to walk the dogs, go shopping, or other activities that involve being on my feet with no foot discomfort at all. I wore them through airport security and had no problem at all removing them and putting them back on. I'm definitely getting another pair when these ones wear out!

column14: I purchased this handbag 6 months ago and was in love with it right away. The color was perfect, the size was just right, and I was thrilled to have a quality handbag that complemented my style. But unfortunately those feelings didn't last long. After about 2 months, the lining began to tear. After about 3 months, the rubber or whatever material that lines the edges of the bag began to come off. Then a couple weeks ago, the straps finally gave in and broke. I attempted to fix them but it was useless. I take excellent care of everything I own, especially handbag and shoes, so I was disappointed to realize that no matter what I did, this bag wasn't going to last. column6: UGG Men's Alamar
column14: I bought several Ugg Alamars because they fit great. Two years ago, I destroyed my left heel bone, and even after reconstructive surgery, my left foot is and always will be disfigured. Alamars don't come in half sizes so it's not surprising when buying shoes online that they might be too long or two narrow. When I wear the right shoe, there's definitely some room between the back of my heel and the heel of the shoe. But these are slip-ons and that extra space doesn't bother me at all. The best part is I can fit my much wider left foot into the shoe. The shoes come with two inserts/soles: fleece and leather. The fleece adds extra comfort and is surprisingly cool, even in Arizona's heat.
